ce:section.ce:para:
The preservation effect of the XHC coating on mango is shown in Fig. 6
                        . The weight loss rate, the decay rate, the titratable acidity, the TSS, and the Vc of mango treated with the XHC coating after 7 days of storage were better than the control (Fig. 7
                        ). The XHC coating could not reduce the weight loss rate and the decay rate during mango storage (Fig. 7a, b), but greatly reduced DI at 5 days to 7 days (Fig. 7). This was because DE-CQDs inhibited the growth of microorganisms. Additionally, the charge properties of DE-CQDs improve their dispersion within the XHC film, enhancing the film's barrier properties and UV-blocking capabilities, which further contribute to the preservation of mangoes. Microorganisms can cause the deterioration of the flavor and quality of fruit [54]. The TA of all mango samples coated with XHC was higher than that of the control (Fig. 7d) since the XHC film can inhibit its respiratory intensity. The same phenomenon was obtained by coating carboxymethylcellulose-xanthan gum-flaxseed gum-Polygonatum extracts [26]. The result was verified by inhibiting mango yellowing by XHC (Fig. 6). The TSS of mango treated with XHC was higher than that of the control group (Fig. 7e), indicating that XHC can reduce the loss of TSS. The same phenomenon was obtained by Fan et al. [55]. Meanwhile, the Vc content of mango gradually decreased with increasing storage time (Fig. 7f). However, the Vc content of the mango treated with XHC was significantly better than that of the control in the first five days. Specifically, fresh mangos have a Vc content of 70 mg/100 g. On the third day, the maintenance rate Vc of XHC2 and XHC10 can be achieved at 61 % and 56 %, respectively, more than the control (30 %). On day five, the maintenance rate of Vc of XHC2 and XHC10 can be achieved at 37 % and 33 %, more than the control (31 %). In summary, the results confirm the positive effect of XHC packaging on mango.
